,"1490":"1490","9 Jun 1523":"9. juni 1523","1557":"1557","1535":"1535","1523":"1523","31 July 1535":"31. juli 1535","1553":"1553","1410":"1410","1464":"1464","about 1460":"omkring 1460","1549":"1549","1417":"1417","Totnes, Devon, England":"Totnes, Devon, England, United Kingdom","Payngton, Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom","Paignton, Exeter, Devonshire Co., England":"Exeter, Devon, England, United Kingdom","Exeter, Devonshire Co., England":"Exeter, Devon, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","Exeter, Devon, England":"Exeter, Devon, England","Devon, England":"Devon, England"},"nl":{"about 1460–1557":"circa 1460–1557","1460–1557":"1460–1557","1464–1535":"1464–1535","1484–1523":"1484–1523","1490–1553":"1490–1553","1410–Male":"1410–Overleden","1417–Female":"1417–Overleden","1484":"1484","1460":"1460","1490":"1490","9 Jun 1523":"9 juni 1523","1557":"1557","1535":"1535","1523":"1523","31 July 1535":"31 juli 1535","1553":"1553","1410":"1410","1464":"1464","about 1460":"circa 1460","1549":"1549","1417":"1417","Totnes, Devon, England":"Totnes, Devon, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Payngton, Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Paignton, Exeter, Devonshire Co., England":"Exeter, Devon, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Exeter, Devonshire Co., England":"Exeter, Devon, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England":"England","Exeter, Devon, England":"Exeter, Devon, England","Devon, England":"Devon, England"},"en":{"about 1460–1557":"about 1460–1557","1460–1557":"1460–1557","1464–1535":"1464–1535","1484–1523":"1484–1523","1490–1553":"1490–1553","1410–Male":"1410–Deceased","1417–Female":"1417–Deceased","1484":"1484","1460":"1460","1490":"1490","9 Jun 1523":"9 June 1523","1557":"1557","1535":"1535","1523":"1523","31 July 1535":"31 July 1535","1553":"1553","1410":"1410","1464":"1464","about 1460":"about 1460","1549":"1549","1417":"1417","Totnes, Devon, England":"Totnes, Devon, England, United Kingdom","Payngton, Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom","Paignton, Exeter, Devonshire Co., England":"Exeter, Devon, England, United Kingdom","Exeter, Devonshire Co., England":"Exeter, Devon, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","Exeter, Devon, England":"Exeter, Devon, England","Devon, England":"Devon, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Blackall","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Blackhall  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Blackhall","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from the lands of Blackhall, in the regality of Garioch (Aberdeenshire).","English: habitational name from one or other of numerous minor places called ‘black hall’ (Middle English <i>blak(e) hall</i>) or ‘dark corner of land’ (Middle English <i>blak(e) hale</i>), including Blackhall (Park) in Saint Cuthbert Without (Cumberland), Blackhall in Plymstock (Devon), Black Hall in North Huish (Devon), Blackhall in Sevenoaks (Kent), and some early tenements or halls named Blackhall in Oxford (Oxfordshire)."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":89,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Richard Blackall Mayor of Exeter was born about 1460, in Devon, England, his father, Richard Blackealder, was 52 and his mother, Mrs. Richard Blackealder, was 44. He married Alice Andrews in 1484, in England. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died in 1557, in Exeter, Devon, England, at the age of 98, and was buried in Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"about 1460–1557":"umbes 1460–1557","1460–1557":"1460–1557","1464–1535":"1464–1535","1484–1523":"1484–1523","1490–1553":"1490–1553","1410–Male":"1410–Surnud","1417–Female":"1417–Surnud","1484":"1484","1460":"1460","1490":"1490","9 Jun 1523":"9. juuni 1523","1557":"1557","1535":"1535","1523":"1523"